abstract: PEKING, Oct. 2. -- Dispatches from Sian Foo announce that the Chinese Court is preparing to start for Peking about Oct. 6. abstract: OSSINING, N.Y., Oct. 3. -- Gilman P. Tiffany won the low-score prize to-day in the Qualifying round, of the open tournament given by the Mount Pleasant Field Club. Auchincloss of the Highland Golf Club.

abstract: ANDOVER, Mass., Oct. 4. -- The Rev. Dr. Cecil P.P. Bancroft, head of Phillips Academy and one of the most prominent men in American academic life, died today. abstract: CAMBRIDGE, Oct. 9. -- Harvard defeated Amherst on Soldiers Field to-day by a score of 11 to 0 in a game that was full of the keenest excitement. Amherst held Yale down to a single touch-down a week ago, but the crimson scored twice through good, steady, hard rushing. On the whole, Amherst considers Harvard stronger than Yale in the back field and nearly as good in the line, only not quite so heavy.

abstract: From The London Times. abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Oct. 10. -- It was only by the hardest kind of playing that Pennsylvania this afternoon defeated Virginia by the score of 20 to 5. The Southerners put up one of the fastest and fiercest struggles seen on Franklin Field this season, and made Pennsylvania work hard. After the first score, the Virginians seemed to wake up, and they not only held Pennsylvania, but skirted her ends repeatedly for large gains.

abstract: PRINCETON, N.J., Oct. 16. -- Princeton's football team defeated Dickinson here today by a score of 23 to 0. The game was a hard one throughout and full of unnecessarily rough play by both sides. Dickinson played a good, defensive game in the first half, but the visitors weakened in the final half, and Princeton's better play resulted in two touchdowns and a field goal.

Owing to the mid-monthly Bourse settlement in Paris a demand arose here for remittances on the French account. abstract: Being precluded from challenging next year with the same boat that has just been so narrowly beaten, Sir THOMAS LIPTON will do the next best thing. abstract: CRIPPLE CREEK, Col., Oct. 22 -- A very rich vein of gold has been struck on the famous Klkton mine. Keteham, his owner, broke the world's mile record for a half mile track this afternoon at the Kansas City Driving Club's park. abstract: Edward C. Lewis, President of the Waterbury Farrel Foundry and Machine Company, died on Thursday at his home in Waterbury, Conn.
